Adding a string with special characters (like quotes, commas, new lines, etc.) to a CSV file can be tricky because these characters can disrupt the CSV format. Here's how you can do it in TypeScript, taking into account all the special characters:

1. **Escaping the Special Characters:** 

In CSV files, fields with embedded commas or double-quotes must be enclosed within double-quotes. If the field itself contains a double-quote, it must be escaped by prefixing it with another double-quote. Here's a simple function to perform this operation:

```typescript
function escapeCSV(value: string) {
    let newValue = value;
    if (newValue.includes(',') || newValue.includes('"') || newValue.includes('\n')) {
        newValue = `"${newValue.replace(/"/g, '""')}"`;
    }
    return newValue;
}
```

This function checks whether the string contains a comma, a new line, or a double-quote. If it does, it encloses the entire string in double-quotes and replaces all instances of a double-quote with two double-quotes, effectively escaping them.

2. **Adding to CSV String:**

Now you can use this function to add your string to the CSV:

```typescript
let csvString = ""; // Your existing CSV string

let yourString = "your,string,with,special,characters";

csvString += escapeCSV(yourString) + ","; // Adding to CSV

// If you want to start a new line in the CSV:
csvString += "\n";

// Remember to remove the trailing comma at the end of each line if there is one.
if (csvString[csvString.length - 1] === ',') {
    csvString = csvString.slice(0, -1);
}
```
This will add your string to the CSV string, correctly formatted. If you want to start a new line in the CSV, you can just append "\n" to the CSV string. Make sure to remove the trailing comma at the end of each line.
